  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="11" relname="span">
In many software or web interfaces, we are presented with more peripheral, or non-
essential, information than we can possibly ingest (Maglio and Campbell, 2000).</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="1" relname="elaboration"> 
This &quot;ambient information&quot; can be helpful, interesting or useless to us.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="1" relname="elaboration"> It can be 
presented innocuously or obnoxiously, as in unsolicited pop-up windows.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="13" relname="span"> But what makes 
it memorable?</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="14" relname="span">
Maglio and Campbell (2000) studied the impact of &apos;ticker displays&apos; on primary task 
performance.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="19" relname="span"> The study compared horizontal continuous scrolling (HCS), vertical discrete 
scrolling (VDS, &apos;scroll-stop&apos;) and serial presentation (SP, full text replacement) ticker 
displays.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="7" relname="concession"> It is no great surprise that displays with more movement are more distracting 
and had a more pronounced impact on performance.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="15" relname="span"> But I found it interesting that, 
although the primary task was completed more slowly or with more errors,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="16" relname="span"> all methods 
were equally memorable in the peripheral information presented.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="17" relname="span">
So this study would support the common marketing practice of presenting website ads 
with animation or movement in order to attract the user&apos;s attention.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="18" relname="span"> However, I would 
argue that user satisfaction would be sacrificed in favor of the mighty dollar.</segment>
